Modifying a collection over which you are iterating is *tricky*, and frequently not allowed. It can easily result in problems, since the iterator is usually implemented under the assumption that the collection will not change.

You however do *not* need to iterate over the keys here. You can use the [**`clear()`** method [Django-doc]](https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/dev/topics/http/sessions/#django.contrib.sessions.backends.base.SessionBase.clear):

&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;def logout(request):
    &lt;b&gt;request.session.clear()&lt;/b&gt;
    return redirect(&#39;login&#39;)&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;

This is however not sufficient. Django already made a function to logout a user that will clear the session, delete it, etc. [**`logout(..)`** [Django-doc]](https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/dev/topics/auth/default/#django.contrib.auth.logout). You thus can implement this as:

&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;from django.contrib.auth import logout as &lt;b&gt;auth_logout&lt;/b&gt;

def logout(request):
    &lt;b&gt;auth_logout(request)&lt;/b&gt;
    return redirect(&#39;login&#39;)&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;

